	<h1>Grazing Influences on Selected Soil Attributes in a Sierra Nevada Riparian Meadow</h1>
	<p class="authors">Robert R. Blank<sup>1</sup><br />
	    	Tony Svejcar<sup>2</sup></p>
	<p class="notes"><sup>1</sup>USDA Agricultural Research Service, Exotic and Invasive Weed Research Unit, 920 Valley Road, Reno, NV, 89512; e-mail: blank@scs.unr.edu</p>
	<p class="notes"><sup>2</sup>USDA Agricultural Research Service, Eastern Oregon Agricultural Research Center, HC 71, 4.5, Hwy 205, Burns, OR 97720</p>

	<h2>ABSTRACT</h2>
	<p>We studied the effects of livestock grazing on soil attributes in a riparian meadow of the northern Sierra Nevada. Treatments were livestock exclusion and grazing. Tension lysimeters were placed in the treatments by position (stream edge, midfloodplain, and forest edge), and by soil horizon (A, 2C, and Cg). Lysimeter water was collected twice monthly in April, May, and June during 1990&#8211;93, and anions and cations were quantified. In addition, KCl-extractable nitrate and ammonium, bicarbonate-extractable ortho-P, and root length density were quantified on soil samples in the treatments by position and depth in July 1991 and Sept. 1993. Treatment significantly interacted with landscape position for ammonium (A horizon lysimeters), for sulfate, potassium, calcium, and sodium (2C horizon lysimeters), and for magnesium and calcium (Cg horizon lysimeters). The grazed forest edge position had significantly greater bicarbonate-extractable ortho-P than the excluded treatment in July of 1991. Potassium-chloride extractable nitrate was significantly greater in the grazed treatment at 0&#8211;25 cm, than in the corresponding excluded treatment in Sept. of 1993. Treatment effects were largely constrained to the forest edge position. Root length density was not affected by grazing. Grazing-induced changes in soil attributes may be linked to landscape redistribution of plant material and elements from salt blocks via livestock feces and urine.</p>
	<dl class="glossary">
		<dt>KEY TERMS: </dt>
		<dd>ammonium, calcium, potassium, sulfate, potassium, root length density</dd>
	</dl>
	<h2>INTRODUCTION</h2>
	<p>Although relatively small in areal extent, riparian areas in the western United States constitute a large proportion of an ecosystem's biotic diversity, water storage, and primary productivity (Warner and Hendrix, 1984). The impact of grazing livestock on riparian ecosysrems has caused considerable concern. Research addressing these concerns has been multifaceted but is centered on grazing-induced vegetational changes, decline in soil health, loss of biotic diversity, loss of fisheries habitat, reduced stream water quality, and changes in stream hydrology (Kauffman and Krueger, 1984).</p>
	<p>We are unaware of any studies that have examined the influence of livestock grazing on the chemistry of the soil-solution. Moreover, few studies have addressed the influence of livestock grazing on areal distribution of soil chemical properties in such spatially diverse habitats as riparian areas. We believe such a study is warranted given the linkage of changes known to occur in soil physical properties and vegetational characteristics as a consequence of livestock grazing with processes such as nutrient mineralization rates, soil redox status, and the kinetics of denitrification. Our purpose was to measure the influence of grazing in a montane meadow on selected soil attributes, emphasizing the chemistry of the soil-solution, and taking into account floodplain position, year, month, and soil depth.</p>
	<h2>MATERIALS AND METHODS</h2>
	<h3>Site Characteristics</h3>
	<p>The study area is along the upper reach of Big Grizzly Creek (120&#176; 37 W 39&#176; 59 N). Big Grizzly Creek is about 1 m in width and the associated montane meadow ranges from about 150 to 500 m in width. The surrounding uplands are forested by lodgepole pine (<em class="ital">Pinus contorta</em> ssp. <em class="ital">murrayana</em> [Grev. & Balf.] Critchf.), white fir (<em class="ital">Abies concolor</em> [Gordon & Glend.] Lindley), and Jeffrey pine (<em class="ital">Pinus jeffreyi</em> Grev. & Balf.). Meadow vegetation consists of Kentucky bluegrass (<em class="ital">Poa pratensis</em> L.), baltic rush (<em class="ital">Juncus balticus</em> wild.), Nebraska sedge (<em class="ital">Carex nebrascensis</em> Dewey) and tufted-hairgrass (<em class="ital">Deschampsia caespitosa</em> [L.] Beauv.). Nebraska sedge dominates very poorly drained areas along the stream, other graminoids increase in poorly drained mid-floodplain positions, and forbs increase in the better drained floodplain-upland interface. Site elevation is 1,800 m. Long-term average precipitation is 89 cm per year (s.d. = 34). During the study period of 1990&#8211;1993, precipitation was considerably less than average 3 of the 4 years. The soil temperature regime is frigid based on thermistor data collected in 1993&#8211;1994. The high organic soils are silt loam to silty clay in texture and classified as Typic Humaquepts (Blank et al., 1995).</p>
	<h3>Treatments</h3>
	<p>Prior to our experiment, the grazing system was season long (June, July, and August) with up to 80 percent forage utilization. Treatments (2 replicates) were livestock exclusion (25 by 100 m) and moderate grazing (42.5 by 100 m). Moderately grazed treatments were designed to leave about 1,000 kg/ha of vegetation which was accomplished by short-term (7 to 14 d) of high stocking density (Huber et al., 1995). All paddocks included portions of Big Grizzly Creek. Depending on the particular year's vegetation phenology, the grazing treatments were applied from mid-June to August. Treatments were initiated in 1989.</p>
	<h3>Lysimeter Installation and Sampling</h3>
	<p>Lysimeters were constructed using 7.6 cm diameter, 0.63 cm thick porous ceramic plates with 10 &#181;m pore diameter. Duplicate lysimeters were placed in excluded and grazed paddocks at three landscape positions: forest edge, mid-floodplain, and stream edge. The stream edge lysimeters were placed approximately 1 m from the stream channel on a small bench. The mid-floodplain lysimeters were placed about 20 m north of the stream channel. The forest edge lysimeters were placed about 40 m north of the stream channel and about 10 m south of the forest boundary. Lysimeters were placed: (1) 10 cm below the soil surface in the A horizon, (2) within a 2C, tephra-rich horizon, which lays directly atop a paleosol 3Btgb or 2Btb argillic horizon at approximately 60 cm (forest edge and mid-floodplain positions only), and (3) in the gleyed Cg horizon zone (approximately 120 cm deep in forest edge and mid-floodplain position, but only 60 cm deep in the stream edge position). Lysimeters were installed in August 1989. Lysimeter water was extracted using a hand vacuum pump, with the first few mL discarded. Lysimeters were sampled when conditions allowed in 1990, 1991, 1992, and 1993. In most years, the soil was too dry to sample beyond June. For this reason we will report on lysimeter chemistry for the months of April, May, and June, the months when most plant growth occurred during the study period.</p>
	<h3>Other Measured Attributes</h3>
	<p>In July 1991, soils were sampled with a bucket auger (two replicates) by landscape position, depth, and treatment. Landscape positions were stream edge (5 m farther from the stream than where the lysimeters were placed), mid-floodplain, and forest edge. Depths were 0&#8211;20, 20&#8211;40, and 40&#8211;60 cm. Soil samples were again collected in September 1993 near the previous landscape positions, by depth (0&#8211;25 and 25&#8211;50 cm), and by treatment (grazed and excluded). Samples were air-dried in a glasshouse and lightly crushed to pass a 2-mm sieve, homogenized, and stored in paper cartons until analyzed. For root length density, uniform volume samples (three replicates) were taken from excluded and grazed paddocks by position and depth as above. Roots were separated from the soil using a commercial root washer (Gillison's Fabrication, Benzonina, MI) and the total root length was measured with a commercial root length scanner (Hawker de Havilland Victoria Limited, Melbourne, Australia) with corrections made for dead roots.</p>
	<h3>Laboratory</h3>
	<p>Lysimeter samples were taken to the laboratory and kept refrigerated between analyses; all analyses were completed in less than 3 days. Anions and cations were quantified by ion chromatography (Dionex Corp., 1986, 1988) and ortho-P by molybdenum blue chemistry (EPA, 1979). For soil analyses we used: (1) bicarbonate extraction for ortho-P with molybdenum blue chemistry (Olsen and Sommers, 1982) and (2) 0.5 M KCl extraction (Keeney and Nelson, 1982) for nitrate (ion chromatography quantification) and ammonium (membrane diffusion colorimetric procedure).</p>
	<h3>Statistical Analyses</h3>
	<p>A variety of unbalanced factors for the lysimeter part of the experiment necessitated performing multiple analyses. For the middle lysimeters, a four-way repeated measures ANOVA design was used with the following factors: treatment (grazed and excluded), position (mid-floodplain, and forest edge), year (1990, 1991, 1992, 1993), and month (April, May and June) with repeated measure on year and month. Further analyses of different nutrient concentrations for the shallow and deep lysimeters and combining all years, for the factors of treatment (grazed and ungrazed), landscape position (stream edge, mid-floodplain, and forest edge), and month (April, May, and June) were conducted using a three-way repeated measure analysis of variance design with repeated measures on month. Duncan's New Multiple Range Test was used as the multiple comparison test for either an interaction or main effect when significant (P &le; 0.05) ANOVA F-test results were obtained. For the soil attributes measured separately, a three-way completely randomized ANOVA (treatment, position, and depth) was used. For a significant F-test, Fisher&#39;s protected LSD was used to separate means. Figures were prepared using only the highest order significant interactions which included treatment.</p>
	<h2>RESULTS</h2>
	<h3>Lysimeter Data</h3>
	<p>Of all the solutes quantified, ammonium was the only solute with a significant (P &#8804; 0.05) treatment effect for lysimeters placed in A horizons. Concentration of ammonium from excluded forest edge lysimeters was significantly greater than that extracted from the grazed forest edge lysimeters (<a href="#fig1">Fig. 1</a>, A). Sulfate, potassium, calcium, and sodium, extracted from lysimeters placed within 2C horizons (forest edge and mid-floodplain positions), all had significant treatment &#215; landscape position interactions (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, B&#8211;E). Grazed mid-floodplain sites had significantly greater sulfate than corresponding livestock excluded values. For the forest edge lysimeter sites, the excluded treatment had significantly more potassium and significantly less calcium and sodium than corresponding values for the grazed treatment. For lysimeters placed in Cg horizons, there was a significant treatment &#215; position interaction for magnesium and calcium (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, F and G). At the forest edge position, the grazed treatment had significantly more magnesium and calcium than the excluded treatment.</p>
	<h3>Lysimeter Data</h3>
	<p>Of all the solutes quantified, ammonium was the only solute with a significant (P &#8804; 0.05) treatment effect for lysimeters placed in A horizons. Concentration of ammonium from excluded forest edge lysimeters was significantly greater than that extracted from the grazed forest edge lysimeters (<a href="#fig1">Fig. 1</a>, A). Sulfate, potassium, calcium, and sodium, extracted from lysimeters placed within 2C horizons (forest edge and mid-floodplain positions), all had significant treatment &#215; landscape position interactions (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, B&#8211;E). Grazed mid-floodplain sites had significantly greater sulfate than corresponding livestock excluded values. For the forest edge lysimeter sites, the excluded treatment had significantly more potassium and significantly less calcium and sodium than corresponding values for the grazed treatment. For lysimeters placed in Cg horizons, there was a significant treatment &#215; position interaction for magnesium and calcium (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, F and G). At the forest edge position, the grazed treatment had significantly more magnesium and calcium than the excluded treatment.</p>

