	<h3>Other Soil Attributes</h3>
	<p>In July of 1991, for the forest edge position, the grazed treatment had significantly greater bicarbonate-extractable ortho-P than the excluded treatment (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, H). In addition, KC1-extractable nitrate and ammonium were very low, averaging 2.0 mg kg<sup>&#8722;1</sup> for nitrate and 4.0 mg kg<sup>&#8722;1</sup> for ammonium with no significant treatment differences. In Sept. of 1993, there were no treatment effects for bicarbonate-extractable ortho-P; however, KCl-extractable nitrate was significantly greater in the grazed treatment at 0&#8211;25 cm, compared to the excluded treatment (<a href="#fig1">Figure 1</a>, I).</p>
	<h2>DISCUSSION</h2>
	<p>There were significant differences in the soil-solution chemistry between the livestock exclusion and livestock grazed treatments. In most cases, treatment-induced changes significantly interacted with landscape position. Most treatment differences occurred in the forest edge position; there were no significant treatment influences in the stream edge position. Given that the entire study area was grazed before the experiment began, it is impossible to deduce if the treatment influences are dominantly a result of continued grazing in the grazed paddocks or from reduced grazing in the excluded paddocks. If continued livestock grazing is responsible for the differences, four aspects should be considered: (1) landscape redistribution of elements via livestock urine and feces, (2) elevated metal contents in urine and feces due to uptake from salt blocks (3) enhanced plant nutrient uptake in response to continual growth following livestock grazing, and (4) alteration of the soil microbial community encouraged by cattle due to cattle feces and urine.</p>
	<p>The research of Huber et al. (1995), contemporaneous with our study in 1992 and 1993, indicates that the majority of livestock grazing time was spent in mid-meadow and stream edge positions because of higher forage production and a greater proportion of highly palatable Carex nebrascensis. However, the forest edge position, especially in 1993, received a greater proportion of loafing use (Huber et al., 1995). Although fecal or urine output was not quantified by landscape position, the higher loafing time spent in the forest edge position suggests that there may be a transfer of chemical elements from stream edge and mid-floodplain positions to the forest edge. Redistribution of plant nutrients to the forest edge position via grazing may partially explain elevated calcium and sodium in the middle lysimeters and higher magnesium and calcium in the deep lysimeters. Higher content of bicarbonate extractable ortho-P in the grazed forest edge positions in 1991 may be similarly explained. Cattle had access in the paddocks to trace mineral salts placed along the forest edge with composition by weight (%) of the following: NaCl 97&#8211;99; Zn 0.85; Mn 0.22; Fe 0.21; Mg 0.10; Cu 0.30; 10.01; Co 0.006 (Huber et al., 1995). The high content of sodium in the salt blocks may be responsible for higher content of sodium in the middle lysimeters of the grazed forest edge position. Removal of vegetation by grazing livestock can, under particular circumstances, stimulate vegetative growth greater than that of ungrazed controls (McNaughton, 1983). If this overcompensation is applicable to our montane meadow, one would expect that elevated plant uptake of particular mineral elements in the livestock grazed treatments would lower the lysimeter content of these elements. Hearne and Howard-Williams (1988) showed that a high grazing intensity for a short period could stimulate uptake of nitrate by riparian vegetation. The far lower ammonium and potassium content in the forest edge grazed lysimeter water as compared to the excluded treatment is potential evidence for this effect. Activity of nitrogen and sulfur cleaving soil enzymes can increase due to enhanced microbial production caused by cattle feces and urine (Haynes and Williams, 1999). Greater sulfate content in the middle lysimeters of the grazed mid-floodplain position and greater KCl-extractable nitrate in the 0&#8211;25 cm of the grazed treatment may be partially explained in this manner.</p>
	<p>One must also consider that the exclusion of grazing, on the once completely grazed meadow, may be the controlling factor in the treatment differences found. A major mechanism of change once livestock are excluded is the accumulation of plant litter (Popolizio et al., 1994). Increased amounts of vegetation and litter forestall rising soil temperatures, thereby, delaying plant phenology and lowering early season mineralization rates (Sharrow and Wright, 1977; Kaufhan et al., 1983). This grazing exclusion factor may better explain treatment differences found for lysimeter values of sulfate and ammonium and KC1-extractable nitrate then the previous mechanisms explored.</p>
	<p>The observed treatment differences may occur via mechanisms which are highly complex and little studied in riparian ecosystems. Soil meso- and macro-faunal activity greatly influence the rate of litter decomposition and nutrient cycling (Coleman and Crossley, 1995). Treatment differences in the numbers and species composition of such organisms may differentially influence nutrient mineralization rates. For some plant species and communities, grazing can reduce root weight and root exploration (Klepper, 1991). If livestock grazing causes root systems to explore less soil or not extend to as great a depth, reduced plant nutrient uptake and/or reduced vertical transfer of elements, as compared to ungrazed systems, could result. In the period of our study, however, there were no significant grazing effects on root length density (<a href="#fig2">Figure 2</a>). Our results support the conclusions of Manning et al. (1989), that native meadows in this region can have very high root length densities. The dominant species in the two more mesic communities sampled by Manning et. al. were the same species that dominate the stream edge and mid-meadow locations in this study.</p>

